# Disregarding the permits applied for or approved in 1999 (incomplete year or data entry error)

permits = permits[permits.year_approved != 1999]
minus1999 = len(permits)

# Get Boulder city geodata 

# First strategy: wget

import wget

'''
Load up Boulder city limits as a geodataframe

city_limits_url = 'http://www-static.bouldercolorado.gov/docs/opendata/BoulderCityLimits.GeoJSON?_ga=2.13299511.1407779936.1515254811-2059223036.1515254811'
wget.download(city_limits_url, os.path.join(RAWDATA_DIR))

Note: Boulder website returns a '403 Forbidden' error when using the wget method. 
Presumably the site is blocking me. There are other libraries I could use if I have time later. See, e.g.: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/34692009/download-image-from-url-using-python-urllib-but-receiving-http-error-403-forbid/34702897
In the interim, I'm just manually downloading the relevant spatial data files, which is quicker but less elegant
'''

Other things I tried:¶

inside_fp = flood_permits_gdf.within(floodplain)

The within method just returns a list of false values. Bet this could be made to work though.

inside_fp = gpd.overlay(flood_permits_gdf, floodplain, how='difference')

The overlay method apparently only works with sets of polygons, not points, although I suspect that when you do a Select by location operation in Arc, it is actually doing a spatial join in the background.
